                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.6363 Manchuria/271: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-12-21T11:00:00+09:00"
                            >December 21, 1935—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received December 21—1:37 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>249. Peiping’s 231, December 16, 5 p.m. to the Department. Manchurian Oil
                    Monopoly.</p>
                <p>1. The local representatives of the oil companies are of the opinion that the
                    letter from Ohashi to Ballantine definitely shows that the companies cannot
                    expect anything better than an unsatisfactory partial settlement based on the
                    physical value of and ignoring the principle of compensation for loss of
                    business. They therefore believe that the companies should proceed to the filing
                    of claims, possibly through diplomatic channels, as envisaged in the Departments
                    77 [<hi rend="italic">67</hi>] April 24, 7 p.m., paragraph 2. The local
                    representatives have telegraphed in the above sense to their head offices and
                    have suggested that the head offices consult with their respective governmental
                    authorities.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Peiping.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
